Let's now determine the net new long-term debt by squeezing back the formula. First, we will compute the operating cash flow using the information in problem 16.

$$\begin{aligned} 
\text{Operating Cash Flow} &= \text{EBIT} + {\text{Depreciation}} - {\text{Taxes}}\\[5pt] 
&= \text{\$25,000} + {\text{140,000}} - {\text{0}}\\[5pt] 
&= \underline{\underline{\text{\$165,000}}} 
\end{aligned}$$

Third, we will compute the cash flow to stockholders by deducting the dividends and net new equity as shown below:

$$\begin{aligned} \text{Cash Flow to Shareholders} &= \text{Dividends Paid} - {\text{Net New Equity raised}}\\[5pt] 
&= \text{\$102,000} - {\text{0}}\\[5pt] 
&= \underline{\underline{\text{\$102,000}}} 
\end{aligned}

Now that we have computed the cash flow from assets and cash flow to shareholders, let's now compute for the cash flow to creditors by squeezing back of cash flow from assets.

$$\begin{aligned} \text{Cash Flow to Creditors} &= \text{Cash flow from Assets} - {\text{Cash Flow to Shareholders}}\\[5pt] 
&= \text{\$165,000} - {\text{102,000}}\\[5pt] 
&= \underline{\underline{\text{\$63,000}}} 
\end{aligned}
